{{Other uses|genderism (disambiguation)}} {{LGBT sidebar}} '''Genderism''', or '''gender binarism''', is the social system or cultural [[belief]] that [[gender binary|gender is a binary]]: that is, that there are, or should be, only two [[gender]]s—[[masculinity|masculine]] and [[femininity|feminine]]—with the aspects of one's gender inherently linked to one's genetic [[sex]], or sex [[sex assignment|assigned at birth]].
These aspects may include expectations of dressing, behavior, [[sexual orientation]], names or pronouns, preferred restroom, or other qualities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Beyond the Binary: Gender Identity Activism in Your School|url=https://www.gsanetwork.org/files/getinvolved/BeyondtheBinary-CampaignGuide.pdf|website=GSA Network|publisher=GSA Network|accessdate=October 24, 2015|date=Summer 2010}}</ref> These expectations may reinforce negative [[attitude (psychology)|attitudes]], [[bias]], and [[discrimination]] towards people who display [[gender expression|expression]]s of [[gender variance|gender variance or nonconformity]] or whose [[gender identity]] is incongruent with their birth sex.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McGeeney|first1=Ester|last2=Harvey|first2=Laura|title=The Palgrave Handbook of the Psychology of Sexuality and Gender|date=2015|publisher=Palgrave Handbooks|pages=149–162}}</ref>
Genderism is of particular relevance to individuals who fall within the [[transgender]] spectrum, and is an [[ideology]] underlying [[transphobia]] and [[trans bashing]].<ref>Transgender and Transsexual Identities: The Next Strange Fruit—Hate Crimes, Violence and Genocide Against the Global TransCommunities, Jeremy D. Kidd & Tarynn M. Witten, Journal of Hate Studies [Vol.6:31. June 2008] 31-63.</ref> Much like how transphobia is parallel to [[homophobia]], genderism is parallel to [[heterosexism]],<ref name="Steinberg2009">{{cite book | author = Shirley R. Steinberg | title = Diversity and Multiculturalism: A Reader | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=txRWlIvanPsC&pg=PA229 | accessdate = 10 September 2012 | date = 1 April 2009 | publisher = Peter Lang | isbn = 978-1-4331-0345-2 | pages = 229–230}}</ref><ref name="BeemynRankin2011">{{cite book | author1 = Genny Beemyn | author2 = Susan R. Rankin | title = The Lives of Transgender People | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nY4OqQayCEsC&pg=PA89 | accessdate = 10 September 2012 | date = 1 November 2011 | publisher = Columbia University Press | isbn = 978-0-231-51261-9 | pages = 89–90}}</ref><ref name="Sue2010">{{cite book | author = Derald Wing Sue | title = Microaggressions and Marginality: Manifestation, Dynamics, and Impact | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7WZxpPnnjzkC&pg=PA224 | accessdate = 11 September 2012 | date = 26 July 2010 | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | isbn = 978-0-470-49139-3 | page = 224}}</ref><ref name="The Psychology Of Prejudice And Discrimination">{{cite book | title = The Psychology Of Prejudice And Discrimination | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=cFyumt--jwIC&pg=RA2-PA210 | accessdate = 11 September 2012 | publisher = ABC-CLIO | isbn = 978-0-275-98234-8 | page = 2| year = 2004 }}</ref> or the belief that heterosexuality is the superior or more desirable sexual orientation in comparison to homosexuality, bisexuality, etc. Another related concept is [[heteronormativity]], the notion that the masculine and feminine genders as well as [[heterosexual]] orientation are the social norm.
== In the LGBT community == Within the [[LGBT]] community, genderism may create institutionalized structures of power, and individuals who identify outside traditional gender binaries may experience discrimination and harassment within the LGBT community.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Farmer|first=Laura Boyd|last2=Byrd|first2=Rebekah|date=2015-10-02|title=Genderism in the LGBTQQIA Community: An Interpretative Phenomenological Analysis|journal=Journal of LGBT Issues in Counseling|volume=9|issue=4|pages=288–310|doi=10.1080/15538605.2015.1103679|issn=1553-8605}}</ref> Most of this discrimination stems from societal expectations of gender that are expressed in the LGBT community. But many LGBT people<ref name=":0" /> and many youth activist groups advocate against genderism within the LGBT community.<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Schindel|first=Jennifer E.|title=Gender 101— beyond the binary: Gay-straight alliances and gender activism|journal=Sexuality Research and Social Policy|volume=5|issue=2|pages=56–70|doi=10.1525/srsp.2008.5.2.56|year=2008}}</ref>
