{{BLP sources|date=March 2015}}
{{Infobox person |name = Jeffrey Ian Ross |image = |caption = Jeffrey Ian Ross |birth_name = Jeffrey Ian Ross |occupation = [[Professor]], [[Author]], [[Criminologist]] }}
'''Jeffrey Ian Ross''', Ph.D. is a scholar, professor, and criminologist specializing in the fields of policing, corrections, political crime, violence, abnormal-extreme criminal behavior, and crime and justice in [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian]] communities. Since 1998 Ross has been a professor at the [[University of Baltimore]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty Directory|url=http://www.ubalt.edu/cpa/faculty/alphabetical-directory/jeffrey-ian-ross.cfm|work=University of Baltimore|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref> He is currently the co-chair of the Division of Critical Criminology of the [[American Society of Criminology]]. Ross is an award winning author, co-author, editor, and co-editor of numerous books.<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 Outstanding Reference Sources List: Reference publications for small and medium-sized public and academic libraries|url=http://rusa.ala.org/blog/2015/02/01/2015-outstanding-reference-sources-list-reference-publications-for-small-and-medium-sized-public-and-academic-libraries/|website=RUSA News|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>
==Education== In 1979, Ross gained admittance to the pre-University program at the [[University of Toronto]], graduating in 1985 with a [[bachelor's degree]] in Political Science and Psychology.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeffrey Ian Ross CV|url=http://www.jeffreyianross.com/|website=JeffreyianRoss|publisher=Jeffrey Ian Ross|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> While attending the University of Toronto, Ross worked first as a crisis intervention counselor at [[Toronto East General Hospital]] and then both part-time and full-time for four years at Metro Toronto Forensic Services, a state run correctional facility.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeffrey Ian Ross CV|url=http://www.jeffreyianross.com/|website=JeffreyianRoss|publisher=Jeffrey Ian Ross|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> In 1985, Ross began his [[Political science#Overview|master's of political science degree]] at the University of Colorado (Boulder) under the supervision of [[Ted Robert Gurr]]. He graduated with a Ph.D. in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeffrey Ian Ross CV|url=http://www.jeffreyianross.com/|website=JeffreyianRoss|publisher=Jeffrey Ian Ross|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref>
==Career== From 1990-1991, while completing his doctorate, Ross worked as Research Associate at the International Center for Comparative Criminology at the [[University of Montreal]]. He began as an Assistant Professor of Political Science at the [[University of Lethbridge]], Alberta in 1991. Two years later, Ross worked as an Assistant Professor for the Department of Criminal Justice Sciences, [[Kent State University]]. From 1995-1998, he worked as Social Science Analyst for the National Institute of Justice. He later started as a Visiting Professor in the Division of Criminology, Criminal Justice, and Social Policy at the [[University of Baltimore]] in 1998; after fourteen years, he was promoted to Full Professor in the School of Criminal Justice at University of Baltimore.<ref>{{cite web|title=Teaching|url=http://www.jeffreyianross.com/TEACHING.html|work=Jeffrey Ian Ross Bio|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref> Ross is the co-chair of the Division on Critical Criminology of the American Society of Criminology.<ref>{{cite web|title=Executive|url=http://divisiononcriticalcriminology.com/about/executive/|website=ASC Division on Critical Criminology|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>
===Oppositional political terrorism=== His earliest research is in the field of oppositional political terrorism (OPT). Ross has specialized in the causal dynamics of OPT. Using quantitative research, Ross developed Attributes of Terrorism in Canada (ATIC), the first data base on OPT in Canada, which was later acquired by the Solicitor General of Canada. This research led Ross to be an expert witness for the Canadian Senate's Special Committee on Terrorism and Public Safety (1986). This source of data, was used in a series of quantitative research studies Ross conducted during the late 1980s and early 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Behind Bars, Beyond Bars, and Convict Criminology|url=http://www.blogtalkradio.com/theprisonshow/2012/03/24/behind-bars-beyond-bars-and-convict-criminology|accessdate=20 May 2014|newspaper=The Prison Show|year=2012}}</ref>
===Policing=== In the field of policing, Ross has examined the challenges facing police departments operating in both western and non-western communities; how incidents of police violence/excessive force come to public attention, and whether this sets an agenda for the police organization to change; and the myths of community policing. Ross has written two books in this area: ''Making News of Police Violence'' (Praeger, 2000), and ''Policing Issues: Challenges and Controversies'' (Jones and Bartlett, 2011).<ref>{{cite news|title='Beyond Bars' Amid Bad Times|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=106550398|accessdate=20 May 2014|newspaper=NPR Books|date=13 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Books by Jeffrey Ian Ross|url=https://www.amazon.com/Jeffrey-Ian-Ross/e/B000AQ10W6/ref=dp_byline_cont_book_1|website=Amazon.com|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>
===Corrections=== Ross’ research in the area of [[corrections]] has focused on understanding problems in this branch of the criminal justice system. Ross is also interested in high security prisons, and edited ''The Globalization of Supermax Prisons'' (Rutgers University Press, 2013). Ross is the co-author of ''Behind Bars: Surviving Prison'' (Alpha Books, 2002) and ''Beyond Bars: Rejoining Society After Prison'' (Alpha Books, 2009).<ref>{{cite web|title=Nutraloaf: Cruel and Unusual Punishment?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cfirwzi_Muc|work=The Alyona Show|accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Books by Jeffrey Ian Ross|url=https://www.amazon.com/Jeffrey-Ian-Ross/e/B000AQ10W6/ref=dp_byline_cont_book_1|website=Amazon.com|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref> Ross is co-founder of the Convict Criminology movement in the field of criminology/criminal justice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Convict Criminology|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/237080265_Convict_Criminology|website=Research Gate|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>
===Political crime/state crime=== Ross wrote ''The Dynamics of Political Crime'' (Sage, 2002), and the follow up book ''Introduction to Political Crime'' (Policy Press, 2012). In the field of state crime, the bulk of Ross’ research has focused on the problem of controlling state crime. This has led to two edited books: ''Controlling State Crime: An Introduction'', (Transaction Publishers, 2000) and ''Varieties of State Crime and Its Control'' (Criminal Justice Press, 2000).<ref>{{cite news|first=WMAR |last=Staff|title=Amber Alert has evolved into vital tool in finding abducted children|url=http://www.abc2news.com/news/region/baltimore-county/amber-alert-has-evolved-into-vital-tool-in-finding-abducted-children|accessdate=20 May 2014|newspaper=abc2news.com|date=6 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Books by Jeffrey Ian Ross|url=https://www.amazon.com/Jeffrey-Ian-Ross/e/B000AQ10W6/ref=dp_byline_cont_book_1|website=Amazon.com|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>
===Crime and justice in American Indian communities=== Ross has also published in the area of crime and justice in American Indian communities. This includes (with Larry Gould) ''Native Americans and the Criminal Justice System'' (Paradigm Publishers, 2006), and ''American Indians at Risk'' (ABC-Clio, 2014).<ref>{{cite web|title=Books by Jeffrey Ian Ross|url=https://www.amazon.com/Jeffrey-Ian-Ross/e/B000AQ10W6/ref=dp_byline_cont_book_1|website=Amazon.com|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>
==Publications== Ross has published extensively in the fields of criminology and criminal justice:<ref>{{cite web|title=Books by Jeffrey Ian Ross|url=https://www.amazon.com/Jeffrey-Ian-Ross/e/B000AQ10W6/ref=dp_byline_cont_book_1|website=Amazon.com|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref> <!-- List sorted by date, and then alphabetically within same year --> * ''Controlling State Crime'' (1995/2000) * ''Violence in Canada: Sociopolitical Perspectives'' (1995/2004) * ''Cutting the Edge: Current Perspectives in Radical/Critical Criminology and Criminal Justice'' (1998/2009) * ''Making News of Police Violence: A Comparative Study of Toronto and New York City'' (2000) * ''Varieties of State Crime and Its Control'' (2000) * ''Behind Bars: Surviving Prison'' (2002; with Stephen C. Richards) * ''Convict Criminology'' (2002; with Stephen C. Richards) * ''Dynamics Of Political Crime'' (2002) * ''Native Americans and the Criminal Justice System'' (2006; with Larry Gould) * ''Political Terrorism: An Interdisciplinary Approach'' (2006) * ''Will Terrorism End?'' (2006) * ''Special Problems in Corrections'' (2007) * ''Beyond Bars: Rejoining Society After Prison'' (2009; with Stephen C. Richards) * ''Cybercrime'' (2009) * ''Religion and Violence: An Encyclopedia of Faith and Conflict from Antiquity to the Present'' (2010) * ''Policing Issues: Challenges & Controversies'' (2011) * ''An Introduction to Political Crime'' (2012) * ''Encyclopedia of Street Crime in America'' (2013) * ''The Globalization of Supermax Prisons'' (2013) * ''American Indians at Risk '' (2014)
==Personal life== {{Expand section|date=December 2014}} Ross currently lives in Washington DC with his wife and children.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
